{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 04:43:10.273096", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and context\n- Topology: 1 super-spine (AS 65000), 2 spines, 2 leaves, EBGP-only. Each leaf connects to a host via /24 (10.<pod>.<leaf>.0/24). Inter-router links use /31s from 172.16.0.0/16. FRR on all routers.\n- Hosts of interest: pc_0_0, pc_0_1.\n\n1) Anomaly detection\n- Network-wide reachability tests show generally healthy connectivity with ~0% loss between most hosts.\n- Exception: pc_0_1 exhibits consistent ~50% packet loss to multiple destinations:\n  - From pc_0_1 to 10.0.5.2: 50% loss.\n  - From pc_0_1 to 10.3.2.2: 50% loss in the sampling run; confirmed by a more intensive probe showing 52% loss (24/50 received) with large initial RTT spikes that settle to normal.\n- Other hosts (e.g., pc_0_0) show 0% loss, indicating the problem is localized to traffic involving pc_0_1.\n\n2) Fault localization\n- Control plane appears healthy on the leaf serving pc_0_1 (leaf_router_0_1):\n  - BGP sessions: Up to all eight neighbors, with 31 prefixes received and sent per peer; stable uptime (~3 minutes at time of check). No evidence of route churn or neighbor flaps.\n  - Leaf interface eth2 (to host) link is up at 10G full-duplex; no obvious L1/L2 faults.\n- pc_0_1 interface state:\n  - eth0 link up at 10G full-duplex; no NIC errors reported by ethtool.\n  - ARP cache shows the default gateway (10.0.1.1) in STALE state, which is normal/benign and not indicative of failure by itself.\n  - Critical finding: tc on pc_0_1 eth0 shows a netem qdisc with packet corruption configured:\n    - qdisc netem 8060: root … corrupt 60%\n    - Sent stats consistent with active impairment.\n- Given:\n  - Loss is observed only when pc_0_1 is the sender (multiple destinations affected).\n  - Router BGP/control plane and links are healthy.\n  - No widespread loss for other hosts.\n  - There is explicit packet corruption configured on pc_0_1’s egress.\n- Conclusion: The fault is on host pc_0_1, specifically its eth0 interface queuing discipline.\n\n3) Root cause analysis\n- Root cause: Local host traffic impairment on pc_0_1 due to tc netem configured with corrupt 60% on eth0.\n- Mechanism and impact:\n  - netem corruption affects egress packets from pc_0_1. Corrupted ICMP echo requests will not elicit replies; corrupted echo replies (when others ping pc_0_1) will be dropped at the far end as bad checksum. This produces the observed ~50% packet loss.\n  - Initial large RTTs seen during the 50-ping run likely reflect early ARP/neighbor resolution and transient queue behavior; once resolved, the remaining successful packets have normal 2–4 ms RTTs, but the corruption continues to cause high loss.\n\nEvidence summary (key outputs)\n- Reachability: pc_0_1 shows 50% loss to multiple destinations; others generally 0% loss.\n- pc_0_1 -> 10.3.2.2 (50 pings @ 100ms): 52% loss, RTT min/avg/max = 2.445/110.527/827.050 ms (initial spikes then normal).\n- pc_0_1 eth0:\n  - ip addr: eth0 UP with qdisc netem.\n  - tc -s qdisc show dev eth0: qdisc netem … corrupt 60%.\n  - ethtool eth0: Link detected: yes; 10000Mb/s, Full-duplex.\n- leaf_router_0_1:\n  - show ip bgp summary: All 8 EBGP neighbors Established, 31 prefixes, no backlog (InQ/OutQ 0).\n  - eth2 link: up at 10G, no errors.\n\nAssessment of network health\n- Control plane: Healthy (EBGP neighbors up, prefixes exchanged as expected).\n- Fabric data plane: Healthy for hosts other than pc_0_1 (no widespread loss or latency issues).\n- Localized issue: Severe packet loss isolated to pc_0_1 due to intentional/accidental traffic impairment (tc netem corrupt 60%) on its NIC.\n\nConclusion\n- Anomaly confirmed: Yes — significant loss seen from pc_0_1.\n- Faulty device: pc_0_1 (host), interface eth0.\n- Root cause: tc netem configuration applying 60% packet corruption on pc_0_1 eth0, leading to high observed packet loss. No evidence of faults in the leaf/spine/super-spine routing or links.", "generation_